element.name: Basic Principle 1: The Patient Comes First
element.documentation:
*Motivation The starting point in healthcare is that the patient comes first. It must be noted, however, that today processes are typically devised and designed by the care provider. This can lead to obstacles for the patient with respect to access to care and understanding and influencing the care process.
*Rationale The hospital derives its raison d’être from the needs of the patient. The services are therefore focused on satisfaction and best results for the patient and the reduction of costs for the hospital (value-based healthcare).
*Implications The care process is organized from the perspective of the patient, so in terms of services for the patient, this means: · — Information about the key care processes should be available to the patient — Care provision is patient-friendly, service-oriented, and professional Many logistical processes underlying the provision of care are not important to communicate to the patient – he or she must be confronted with this as little as possible and not be bothered by it; this means: — The logistical processes should be in the best interest of the patient while also being practical for the provider — Patients are helped quickly, not unnecessarily referred, and need only provide information once – the client file must therefore be complete and known to every actor (insofar as privacy rules are followed) The patient decides, in consultation with his or her provider, the course of care, which means: — Healthcare providers proactively inform the patient — Patient privacy is guaranteed; healthcare providers must comply with the healthcare privacy rules and regulations of the country where care is provided — The patient can go to a clear, open, and friendly counter/contact point for questions and complaints

element.name: Basic Principle 2: The Hospital Functions in a Network of Care Providers
element.documentation:
*Motivation Healthcare is provided in a network of formal and informal care giving. Networks exist in hospitals, in hospital systems, and in larger ecosystems. In a network, caregivers are separated by few if any degrees of separation. Operational and information management are still too focused on efficiency within an organization.
*Rationale Typically, patient care is delivered by formal and/or informal caregivers in a network. Several care providers are involved in the care of a patient and they do not always work in a hospital or in the same hospital. By organizing operational management and information management through cooperation, the collaborating partners work together quickly and efficiently for the benefit of the patient. Both the operational management around the patient and the required information exchange are designed for interoperability across the boundaries of care lines.
*Implications · Healthcare is increasingly developing in networked care – cooperation with collaboration partners in the service of the patient · Anticipating and acting on internal and external developments and social involvement is a motivation of the hospital · Information exchange in healthcare is essential to guarantee the quality and continuity of healthcare – information provision must therefore be up-to-date and set up for maximum interchangeability · Patient care, research, and education reinforce and build on each other in a learning healthcare system; patients, healthcare providers, researchers, teachers, and students work together, which also requires adequate information exchange

element.name: Basic Principle 3: Clear and Unambiguous Data Capture at the Point of Care
element.documentation:
*Motivation Most hospitals experience data collection as burdensome. This is caused by, among other things, inefficient data management. Frequently, data is requested and stored multiple times, in multiple systems, and multiple places, unnecessarily. This is because data is often not coded using a standardized format. This limits the possibilities for reuse (which makes repeated data collection and entry necessary) and can lead to interpretation errors.
*Rationale Data and information are among the most valuable resources in an organization. Unambiguous and one-time registration of data helps ensure that everyone has access to the same facts, including where key data is located. As a result, scientific research becomes easier. Patients no longer need to tell the same story every time. Because information is more widely available and usable, within boundaries set by safety and security protocols, patients and personal caregivers can exercise more control over care, permissioned providers can access necessary data when and where needed, and the quality of care may increase.
*Implications · Data management is organized according to FAIR principles; this means: — Findable: data is easy to find (again), identifiable, and traceable to the source; data is accessed quickly, flexibly where possible, cautiously, and checked where necessary — Accessible: data is shared and is accessible to authorized persons; authorization is granted in accordance with legislation and policy; storage and disclosure of data is done centrally where possible, locally where necessary — Interoperable: data has a common vocabulary and clear definitions – we opt for uniformity and (international) standards where possible, and local nuances where necessary — Reusable: data is recorded once at the source for multiple use – data from one domain can be reused in one or more other domains · One integrated longitudinal view of the patient (patient access and management, integrity, unambiguous, reusable longitudinal file) · The purpose for which data is used and reused is compatible with the purpose for which data is collected (purpose limitation); customers have access to the data that they keep about patients, who has access to it, and who has edited it or consulted it · Data is requested from the source and as much as possible use is made of the patient’s master record · When in doubt about the correctness of data in a system, every user (patient or healthcare provider) must be able to report this to the source holder of that system, after which the source holder will adjust the data if necessary · Data is created, used, and stored in accordance with the specifications of the healthcare information building blocks Around this basic principle, a program called “Registration at the Source” was started January 2014 in collaboration between Nictiz and the eight University Medical Centers in the Netherlands. For more information, see https://amigo.nictiz.nl/programma/registratie-aan-de-bron.

element.name: Basic Principle 4: Information Provision is Flexible, Secure, and Sustainable
element.documentation:
*Motivation Change happens faster and comes from more sources (including government, technology, and users) than ever before. Information exchange is often an impediment that delays responses to changing circumstances and needs of professionals and customers.
*Rationale The provision of information must support the continuous improvement and innovation of care.
*Implications · The provision of information is flexible · The provision of information is increasingly service-oriented, based on loosely-coupled components; systems are synchronized and integrated in real time via an integration platform · When multiple applications are used, the context of patient data must be clear · Information provision uses national guidelines, generic standards, and proven solutions · Information provision is secure and complies with laws and regulations and the standards for information security · Measures have been put in place to guarantee the continuity of the service throughout the network of care · Promote the shared use of applications · Reuse comes before buying, before making · The provision of information is set up in a sustainable and responsible manner

element.name: Basic Principle 5: Quality can be Deduced from the Care Process
element.documentation:
*Motivation To be able to manage their care process, patients/customers need insight into the quality of care provided. Only then can they base their choices on the right information. But the registration burden in healthcare is high and the supply of (extra) quality information increases this burden even more. Data to be recorded must have added value for the (care for) the patient or contribute to determining the (quality of) care provided.
*Rationale By realizing the desired transparency with unambiguous, anonymous data from the primary source registration, (satisfaction) measurements, and information to be derived from this, the registration burden can be limited. This also applies to transparency towards the government, insurers, or other organizations involved in healthcare.
*Implications · (Re)design of processes based on value for the patient (outcomes, outcome) · Quality registrations and other deliveries entail as little extra work as possible; this means: — The quality records are based on information from the primary process — Different quality registrations request similar information in the same way — Record data in accordance with the healthcare information building blocks · Data capturing details of the patient experience is also required for complete transparency; this means: — Structural satisfaction and outcome measurements of the patient as part of the process — Drawing up and adjusting questionnaires in consultation with the patient, so that attention is paid to what they find important · The technical design of systems should ensure, to the extent possible, that administrative burden is kept to a minimum; this means: — Data is recorded unambiguously to enable multiple use (see also Basic Principle 3) — For optimum user-friendliness, interfaces are designed in close collaboration with end users; e.g., using principles from interaction design and user experience design · Healthcare providers record information clearly and once; this means: — Do not record something that has already been recorded — Providers should be aware of the usefulness and necessity of this — Structural support for caregivers in the use of quality improvement systems — Use semantic standards and the healthcare information building blocks

element.name: (Re)design of processes is based on value for the patient (outcomes-based).
element.documentation:
* Reason/Dilemma How do we organize care in such a way that teams can take joint responsibility for the best outcomes of care.
*Rational Improving the outcome of care and the patient experience in delivering care.
*Implications - The patient as a partner: strengthening the involvement of the patient (and family/network) in his treatment and care, and in improving it. If desired, the patient can take the lead in this; - Interprofessional cooperation: providing care and improving it as the joint responsibility of all professionals involved in hospitals, chains and regional networks.

element.name: Applications are designed to be intuitive and to help the user.
Applications are service- oriented and loosely- coupled.
element.documentation:
* Reason/Dilemma The provision of information does not adapt quickly and flexibly to changes in the approach and participation of the patient. Information provision is too rigid. Adjustments are laborious and complex due to many internal dependencies. Similar functionality occurs in multiple applications. Reuse of functionality is not always possible.
*Rational A more service-oriented information provision responds more quickly to changing circumstances and new requirements and wishes.
*Implications - Applications make their functionality and data available through services based on open standards. Open standards provide the best basis for integration because they are widely supported in the market. Open standards also prevent supplier dependencies.

element.name: Clear agreements are made about the type of data to be exchanged.
element.documentation:
* Reason/Dilemma Data is now often exchanged without agreement on the meaning of the data. Data is therefore misinterpreted.
*Rational Unambiguous agreements about the data that are exchanged are necessary for a correct understanding and interpretation of the data. Without these agreements, information exchange can pose a risk to patient safety.
*Implications - In ICT terms, this means specifying a dataset that specifies which data types are needed and how they are captured. - For example, implementation of information standards https://www.nictiz.nl/standaardisatie/informatiestandaarden

element.name: Data from the care process can be used for derived objectives, such as governance, control, quality indicators, administration, finance, and research.
Data is a business asset and is carefully managed.
element.documentation:
* Reason/Dilemma Traditionally, data has been tied to one specific application. The understanding of this data lay within the application. With more and more cooperation and information exchange, this is no longer valid.
*Rational Data is a valuable asset. They must therefore be managed in such a way that the customers in an organization (or chain) have access to the right data of the right quality at the right time, in a safe manner. Data is the basis of information, knowledge and decisions, and is therefore of crucial importance for the correct and efficient functioning of healthcare.
*Implications - Monitoring the quality of data; - Using uniform definitions for data; - Setting up data governance.

The choice of control over his own process is a patient's right, not an obligation. The patient can hand over control to an informal carer, case manager or the attending physician.
*Rational - Increase customer satisfaction; - Increase effectiveness of care; - The patient can exert influence himself.

In addition, it is useful within the chain if functionality is available to support the collaboration between the patient's healthcare providers (e.g. logbook, chat functionality, consent registration, audit trail, integration of self-monitoring and connection to PHE).
*Implications - An integrated overview is available for the care providers in the chain, in which the data are arranged around the clinical picture and the patient (and not around the care provider)

element.name: Account for social entrepreneurship
element.documentation: To be accountable for social topics such as sustainability, mobility, aging.

element.name: Accountable for performance
element.documentation: To be accountable for the extent to which performance goals are met.

element.name: Administer/use medication
element.documentation: Providing and/or introducing medication to be taken at a specific time, according to agreement and route of administration (oral, injection, anal, etc.). May also concern the administration of nutrition via an IV or tube and the use of self-administered medication.

element.name: Administration of personnel information
element.documentation: Includes personnel registration, time, absenteeism and leave registration, HR costs and return.

element.name: Advise on building and inventory
element.documentation: Preparing, planning, and supervising new construction, rebuilding, and renovation.

element.name: Advise patient
element.documentation: Providing advice to the patient on how to deal with his/her complaints.

element.name: Alert about relevant results
element.documentation: If unanticipated, but relevant findings are made during the research these are reported to the patient or his practitioner.

element.name: Apply for external funding
element.documentation: If necessary, external funding is requested.

element.name: Apply for permits
element.documentation: Permits are applied for if necessary.

element.name: Assess diagnostic testing request
element.documentation: Assessing the request for additional diagnostic testing.

element.name: Assess referral
element.documentation: Taking note of the nature and background of a referral by the (assigned) healthcare provider

element.name: Assess results of additional diagnostic testing
element.documentation: Reading and interpreting the results of diagnostic testing.

element.name: Assess results of additional or own research
element.documentation: Taking note of the results of additional diagnostic tests or results of the examinations carried out by care provider himself and including these in the diagnosis and treatment plan.

element.name: Assess results of peer consultation
element.documentation: Taking note of and assessing the findings made during a consultation with a fellow healthcare provider, and including these in the diagnosis and treatment plans.

element.name: Assess self-management information
element.documentation: Receiving and processing information (eg., measurements, diary and findings) from the patient about their own care process, both digitally and on paper.

element.name: Assign to Caregiver
element.documentation: Assigning a healthcare provider of a (sub)specialty to the patient (as primary).

element.name: Assign to caregiver
element.documentation: Assigning a healthcare provider of a (sub)specialty to the patient (as primary).

element.name: Book hotel service
element.documentation: Request in advance and record a desired service administratively.

element.name: Carry out treatment
element.documentation: Performing treatment including final check, stabilization.

element.name: Check specimen data
element.documentation: Receiving and verifying material data.

element.name: Collect research data and material
element.documentation: Data required for the research is collected and, if necessary, research material is also collected from the patient.

element.name: Collect specimen
element.documentation: Collecting human material (blood, urine, tissue, etc.) required for diagnostic testing.

element.name: Collect treatment outcomes
element.documentation: Collecting information on the treatment provided based on clinical and patient reported measures.

element.name: Compile educational program
element.documentation: Drawing up curriculum and study programming for regular (including medicine, nursing, paramedical) and further education (medical and nursing specializations).

element.name: Complete care request
element.documentation: Comprehensively handling the care request.

element.name: Complete treatment
element.documentation: Completing the treatment (final check-up, stabilization, transfer to another healthcare provider and cleaning up the treatment room).

element.name: Comply with laws and regulations
element.documentation: To be accountable for compliance with applicable legislation and regulations.

element.name: Conduct Additional Diagnostic Testing
element.documentation: Obtaining information about the physical or mental condition of patient in a systematic manner, according to a specific method or technique. Collecting human material/specimen(s) and collecting visual material.

element.name: Conduct market analysis
element.documentation: Examining factors that determine or influence supply and demand.

element.name: Conduct own research
element.documentation: Observing/measuring certain bodily functions such as breathing, blood pressure, heart rate, temperature, fluid balance, reflexes or other aspects of bodily functioning. Also, examination by the care provider as part of the diagnostic consultation.

element.name: Conduct therapy
element.documentation: Carrying out treatment by various therapeutic disciplines (that deal with the treatment or cure of diseases or the alleviation of symptoms) as part of the treatment plan, for example radiotherapy, physiotherapy, speech therapy.

element.name: Content assessment of education
element.documentation: Individual assessment of the quality of education (sometimes quantity) based on established criteria.

element.name: Deliver medication
element.documentation: Dispensing by a pharmacy of a specific drug to a person. Dispensing is the supply of a quantity of a medicinal product to the patient, his administering party or his representative.

element.name: Delivery of data to external parties
element.documentation: Providing data to external parties, such as those involved in the continuum of care, insurers, registries, and governmental entities with jurisdiction.

element.name: Determine Strategy
element.documentation: The strategy describes how the vision will be achieved and indicates a coherent set of policy lines for maintaining continuity in the longer term.

element.name: Determine care needs
element.documentation: Assessing the patient's care needs and determining how they can be delivered. This includes triage in specific contexts.

element.name: Determine diagnosis
element.documentation: To the greatest extent possible, making an unambiguous determination of the nature and cause of the patient's complaints.

element.name: Determine innovation agenda
element.documentation: Determining which innovations should take place to support product and service development.

element.name: Determine mission and vision
element.documentation: A mission defines the raison d'être of an organization and answers the question: Why do we do what we do? The mission is timeless. A vision is a consistent view of the future and indicates the desired situation.

element.name: Determine nursing diagnosis
element.documentation: Deciding a diagnosis that is pertinent to nursing treatment.

element.name: Determine nursing goal (outcome)
element.documentation: Determining the nursing goal.

element.name: Determine nursing plan
element.documentation: Determining a formal process that includes six components: assessment, diagnosis, expected outcomes, interventions, rationale, and evaluation. Documenting these steps ensures effective communication between doctors, nurses, and other healthcare professionals over multiple shifts.

element.name: Determine policy
element.documentation: Determining hospital and/or division policy and specific policy plans such as medical, nursing, department, safety, labor, quality, and environment at strategic, tactical, and operational level.

element.name: Determine production agreements
element.documentation: Coordinating production capacity with health insurers.

element.name: Determine therapeutic diagnosis
element.documentation: Provide the diagnosis.

element.name: Determine therapy goal
element.documentation: Working with the patient to determine the aim of the therapy.

element.name: Determine therapy plan
element.documentation: Deciding on a nursing plan and recording it so that it can be used in communication with the patient and other caregivers.

element.name: Determine transfer/transfer policy
element.documentation: Determining the activities and the necessary information provision for the transfer of patient to home or transfer of patient to another institution.

element.name: Determine treatment advice
element.documentation: Determining and establishing a treatment recommendation.

element.name: Determine treatment options
element.documentation: Determining which treatments are possible for the patient's care needs on the basis of all available data.

element.name: Develop Enterprise Architecture
element.documentation: Developing and refining business, solutions, information, and technology architecture based on desired innovations.

element.name: Develop IT
element.documentation: Develop and test services based on customer requirements, so that the customer gets what he needs. This activity includes change management, engineering and IT projects.

element.name: Develop products and services
element.documentation: Developing new healthcare products and services as well as product management.

element.name: Develop research data set
element.documentation: If clinical data must be collected for the research, researchers and data managers jointly develop the required dataset.

element.name: Develop treatment plan
element.documentation: Determining and establishing a treatment plan (including requests for authorizations from the insurer)).

element.name: Direct management and maintenance of building and inventory
element.documentation: Inventory of supply and demand, from forecast to normative space requirement, multi-year housing plan, efficient and flexible use of space, real estate and land.

element.name: Draft and review legal policy
element.documentation: Drafting legal policy such as privacy policy and ensuring compliance with the policy on the basis of existing legislation.

element.name: Draft research proposal
element.documentation: The researcher or research group draws up a definitive research proposal.

element.name: Draft research protocol/design
element.documentation: Developing a protocol/design for the purpose of conducting a research project.

element.name: Draft transfer
element.documentation: Termination or transfer of care from one healthcare provider to another healthcare provider (including discharge/referral/transfer/death).

element.name: Draw up care plan
element.documentation: Planning implementation of the care request.

element.name: Educate patient
element.documentation: Providing the patient with medical and healthcare information regarding their complaints or conditions.

element.name: Evaluate care
element.documentation: Evaluating the care provided (the result of all treatments) with respect to treatment goals.

element.name: Evaluate education
element.documentation: Evaluation of education and implementation of improvement actions.

element.name: Evaluate nursing results
element.documentation: Evaluating the nursing outcome.

element.name: Evaluate therapy
element.documentation: Evaluating the outcome of the therapy.

element.name: Fundraising and sponsorship
element.documentation: Acquire additional funds and maintain sponsorship relationships.

element.name: Guide participants
element.documentation: Guiding, coaching, counseling, including informal means of imparting knowledge and experience.

element.name: Identify patient
element.documentation: Identifying, can lead to changes in patient data.

element.name: Implementing a nursing plan
element.documentation: Implementing the nursing plan.

element.name: Include publication in publication list
element.documentation: Completed publications are included in a publication list.

element.name: Inform internally and externally
element.documentation: Compiling, collecting and providing information about and to patients, visitors, healthcare professionals, students, researchers, employees, press, etc.

element.name: Inform patient
element.documentation: Informing and advising on, for example, the nature, approach and risk of further examination, treatment options, or surgery that the patient undergoes.

element.name: Invoicing healthcare product

element.name: Maintain contacts

element.name: Maintain medical technology
element.documentation: Technical management (preventive and corrective maintenance) of medical technology such as medical equipment, medical devices including software.

element.name: Manage data of healthcare organizations

element.name: Manage data of healthcare providers
element.documentation: Establishing and maintaining administrative data of healthcare providers.

element.name: Manage health insurers' data
element.documentation: Recording and maintaining administrative data of health insurers.

element.name: Manage knowledge
element.documentation: Making knowledge available and keeping it up to date (publications, professional literature, etc.).

element.name: Manage means of transport

element.name: Manage participant data

element.name: Manage patient data
element.documentation: Recording and maintaining administrative data, such as insurance, personal identification number, etc.

element.name: Manage patient file

element.name: Manage stock

element.name: Manage technical installations

element.name: ANALYSIS OF BODY FLUIDS
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het uitvoeren en verslagleggen van klinisch chemisch laboratorium (KCL) onderzoek.</nl-NL><en-US>The most commonly analyzed fluids are: blood, urine, fluid that surrounds the spinal cord and brain (cerebraospinal fluid), fluid within a joint (synovial fluid). Less often, sweat, saliva and fluid from the digestive tract are analyzed. Sometimes the fluids analyzed are present only if a disorder is present, as when fluid collects in the abdomen, causing ascites, or in the space between the two-layered membrane covering the lungs and lining the chest wall (pleura), casing pleural effusion. </en-US></languages>

element.name: ANALYSIS OF GENETIC MATERIAL
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het uitvoeren en verslagleggen van genetisch onderzoek.</nl-NL><en-US>Usually, cells from skin, blood, or bone marrow are analyzed. Cells are examined to check for abnormalities of chromosomes, genes (including DNA), or both. Genetic testing may be done in the following: · Fetuses: To determine whether they have a genetic disorder · Children and young adults: To determine whether they have a disorder or are at risk of developing a disorder · Adults: Sometimes to help determine the likelihood that their relatives, such as children or grandchildren, will develop certain disorders.</en-US></languages>

element.name: BIOPSY
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het uitvoeren en verslagleggen van biopsie.</nl-NL><en-US>Tissue samples are removed and examined, usually with a microscope. The examination often focuses on finding abnormal cells that may provide evidence of inflammation or of a disorder, such as cancer. Tissues that are commonly examined include skin, breast, lung, liver, kidney, and bone..</en-US></languages>

element.name: ENDOSCOPY
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het uitvoeren en verslagleggen van endoscopisch onderzoek.</nl-NL><en-US>"A viewing tube (endoscope) is used to directly observe the inside of body organs or spaces (cavities). Most often, a flexible endoscope is used, but in some cases, a rigid one is more useful. The tip of the endoscope is usually equipped with a light and a camera, so the examiner watches the images on a television monitor rather than looking directly through the endoscope. Tools are often passed through a channel in the endoscope. One type of tool is used to cut and remove tissue samples. Endoscopy usually consists of passing the viewing tube through an existing body opening, such as the following: · Nose: To examine the voice box (laryngoscopy) or the lungs (bronchoscopy) · Mouth: To examine the esophagus (esophagoscopy), stomach (gastroscopy), and small intestine (upper gastrointestinal endoscopy) · Anus: To examine the large intestine, rectum, and anus (coloscopy) · Urethra: To examine the bladder (cystoscopy) · Vagina: To examine the uterus (hysteroscopy) However, sometimes an opening in the body must be created. A small cut (incision) is made through the skin and the layers of tissue beneath the skin, so that the endoscope can be passed into a body cavity. Such incisions are used to view the inside of the following: · Joints (arthroscopy) · Abdominal cavity (laparoscopy) · Area of the chest between the lungs (mediastinoscopy) · Lungs and pleura (thoracoscopy)"</en-US></languages>

Others include ultrasonography, radioisotope (nuclear) scanning, computed tomography (CT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET), and angiography.</en-US></languages>

element.documentation: managing of knowledge

element.name: LEGAL SUPPORT
element.documentation: Ensuring that the organization operates within the boundaries of legislation and regulations.

element.name: MARKETING
element.documentation: Optimal coordination between the supply and demand of services, including researching social developments that (will) determine the demand, with the aim of assigning as much value as possible to the existing services and responding as well as possible to wishes and opportunities for new or customized services.

element.name: MEASUREMENT OF BODY FUNCTIONS
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het uitvoeren en verslagleggen van functieonderzoeken. </nl-NL><en-US>Often, body functions are measured by recording and analyzing the activity of various organs. For example, electrical activity of the heart is measured with electrocardiography (ECG), and electrical activity of the brain is measured with electroencephalography (EEG). The lungs’ ability to hold air, to move air in and out, and to exchange oxygen and carbon dioxide is measured with pulmonary function tests.</en-US></languages>

element.name: MEDICAL TECHNOLOGY
element.documentation: Maintaining and supporting medical technology.

element.name: MEDICATION
element.documentation: Drug treatment of the patient

element.name: MICROBIOLOGY AND IMMUNOLOGY LAB RESEARCH
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het uitvoeren en verslagleggen van microbiologisch en immunologisch labonderzoek.</nl-NL><en-US>Conducting and reporting microbiological and immunological lab research</en-US></languages>

element.name: NURSING
element.documentation: Treatment of the patient through nursing interventions

element.name: NURSING
element.documentation: Behandeling van de patiënt doormiddel van verzorgende taken.

element.name: OTHER TREATMENTS
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Behandeling niet afgedekt door de overig soorten van behandeling.</nl-NL><en-US>Type of treatment not covered in the other five treatment business function categories.</en-US></languages>

element.name: PARTICIPATION
element.documentation: Participation of the patient in his/her own care process

element.name: PERFORMANCE MANAGEMENT
element.documentation: Create, measure and direct on performance indicators; about care, research and educational services to be provided, as well as research in order to arrive at the right range of services

element.name: PLANNING & CONTROL
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het geheel van activiteiten om te bepalen wat er in een bepaalde periode moet gebeuren (planning), de rapportage daarover en de benodigde bijsturing en uiteindelijke verantwoording over de behaalde resultaat (control).</nl-NL><en-US>The whole of activities to determine what needs to be done in a certain period (planning), the reporting on this and the necessary adjustments and ultimate accountability for the result achieved (control).</en-US></languages>

element.name: PROPERTY AND RESOURCE MANGEMENT
element.documentation: Operating the hospital's buildings and inventory.

element.name: PURCHASE AND GOODS LOGISTICS
element.documentation: Acquiring resources and monitoring agreements about this with the supplier, including the management of stocks.

element.name: QUALITY MANAGEMENT
element.documentation: Guaranteeing the quality of care, research and education and patient safety.

element.name: REFERRALS & TRANSFERS
element.documentation: Referrals and transfer to and from other healthcare providers, including the necessary information exchange

element.name: RESEARCH DEVELOPMENT
element.documentation: Ensuring an accepted research proposal

element.name: RESEARCH IMPLEMENTATION
element.documentation: Het daadwerkelijk uitvoeren van het onderzoek

element.name: RESEARCH PREPARATION
element.documentation: Ensuring that the preconditions for the research are safeguarded.

element.name: RESEARCH PUBLICATION
element.documentation: Draw up and distributing publications related to the research.

element.name: RESEARCH SUPPORT
element.documentation: Administrative and substantive support for investigations.

element.name: SAFETY AND ENVIRONMENT
element.documentation: Managing and optimizing business support, facility safety, quality, health and safety and environmental aspects within the hospital.

element.name: SOCIETAL VALUE CHAIN (VALUE GENERATION RESEARCH)
element.documentation: Making research results (publications, research data) public available and suitable for application in products, processes and services such as interaction with society and private organizations.

element.name: STRATEGY & GOVERNANCE
element.documentation: Determining the mission, vision, strategy and policy, including the policy direction and management

element.name: SURGERY
element.documentation: Surgical procedures as part of the patient's treatment

element.name: TEACHING EVALUATION
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het testen van de resultaten van het onderwijs.</nl-NL><en-US>Evaluating the impact of teaching</en-US></languages>

element.name: TEACHING PERFORMANCE
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Het voorbereiden en uitvoeren van alle direct aan het onderwijs gerelateerde activiteiten.</nl-NL><en-US>Preparing and executing all activities directly related to education.</en-US></languages>

element.name: TEACHING SUPPORT
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Administratief, inhoudelijk, ondersteuning van onderwijs</nl-NL><en-US>Administrative, substantive, educational support</en-US></languages>

element.name: THERAPY
element.documentation: Form of treatment that deals with the treatment or cure of diseases or the relief of symptoms

element.name: TREATMENT
element.documentation: Treatment of the patient

element.name: TREATMENT PLANNING
element.documentation: Determining and setting out a treatment plan

element.name: Activity
element.documentation: There are 2 types of activities, which are ordered and unordered. A certain activity, operation, series of actions with which a certain result can be achieved.

element.name: Additional diagnostic testing
element.documentation: Request for planning and execution of a transfer (admission/discharge/transfer) of a patient.

element.name: Administration agreement
element.documentation: The supply of a medication product to a specific patient (or the administerer or a representative) with the intent that it be used according to a supplied instruction (usually as an implementation of the dispensing request in a medication prescription).

element.name: Advice
element.documentation: The healthcare provider's advice to the patient as a result of the consultation and the diagnostic process (other than treatment).

element.name: Advisory report
element.documentation: Recording of the advice given.

element.name: Agenda
element.documentation: An overview with dates and times in which the scheduled appointments of one specific resource (person or agent) are recorded. A group calendar is an aggregation of multiple calendars.

element.name: Anamnesis report
element.documentation: Recording of the interview between care provider and patient a personal representative or healthcare proxy, in which the care provider asks specific questions about the care demand.

element.name: Anesthesia report
element.documentation: Recording of the anesthesia performed during an operation.

element.name: Annual plan
element.documentation: Accountability for the plan for the coming (financial) year

element.name: Annual report
element.documentation: Accountability of an organization for the course of business in the past (financial) year.

element.name: Appointment
element.documentation: Recording data regarding a patient's appointment with a healthcare provider.

element.name: Appointment request
element.documentation: Request to schedule a contact between a patient and a healthcare provider.

element.name: Article
element.documentation: Commodity and quantity present in a given place, expressed in units or in money

element.name: Balance
element.documentation: Overview of all assets; on the left (assets or debit side) and the debt plus equity on the right side (liabilities or credit side) at any given time

element.name: Building
element.documentation: Building

element.name: Care
element.documentation: Record nursing assistance activities

element.name: Care Report
element.documentation: Record observations of the patient by the caregiver.

element.name: Care Team
element.documentation: A group of caregivers, often from different disciplines, assigned to the patient.

element.name: Care needs
element.documentation: The patient’s care needs aso determined by a healthcare provider.

element.name: Care plan
element.documentation: Care plan includes the diet.

element.name: Certificate
element.documentation: Documentary evidence of a final judgment on the completion of a PhD, study programme, minor or unit of study by an institution. (source HORA)

element.name: Class
element.documentation: A collection of participants carrying out jointly scheduled educational activities.

element.name: Collegiate consultation
element.documentation: Request for opinion or advice from a colleague/health care professional regarding diagnosis or treatment.

element.name: Competence
element.documentation: An integrated whole of knowledge, skills, insight and attitude, which is necessary to realize professional products in a professional context that meet the applicable quality requirements. Competences are composed in character, refer to underlying skill, knowledge and attitude domains and are applied and developed in a context.

element.name: Complaint
element.documentation: A subjective perception of health that is experienced as negative.

element.name: Complaints
element.documentation: All reports concerning complaints about care or services provided.

element.name: Complication
element.documentation: Recording of the unintended and undesired outcomes, during or following the actions of a healthcare provider, that are detrimental to the health of the patient to such an extent that an adjustment of the medical treatment or treatment is necessary, or that irreparable damage has occurred.

element.name: Contract
element.documentation: Official paper with agreements to which those involved must adhere.

element.name: Contraindication
element.documentation: Disorder, illness, or complaint in which a certain therapy, for example medication, may not be used.

element.name: Correspondance
element.documentation: Document with which healthcare providers inform each other about the status of the patient, their medical history and treatment(s), e.g. upon discharge, admission, or other transfer situations.

element.name: Course of disease
element.documentation: Description of the chronological course of the patient's disease process and of the progress of treatment, written down/summarized by the physician.

element.name: Current medication overview
element.documentation: Recording of the current medication use by a patient.

element.name: Cutlery
element.documentation: Description of a work, construction plan

element.name: Data relationship education and care process
element.documentation: Established relationship between education and care process, e.g. supervision of care professional for doctor in training

element.name: Declaration
element.documentation: Account for costs incurred or services rendered

element.name: Delivery
element.documentation: Data for external parties such as healthcare ministries, public health (physical and mental) agencies, public and private insurers, etc.

element.name: Delivery agreement
element.documentation: Description of the delivery conditions

element.name: Development plan
element.documentation: The plan in which the employee records his personal development

element.name: Diagnosis
element.documentation: Recording the name of the disease or condition that a person is believed to be suffering from, as stated by the physician.

element.name: Diagnostics Results
element.documentation: Any result from a diagnostic tests

element.name: Dismissal
element.documentation: Request to terminate the provision of care. This results in an exchange information object or a transfer information object.

element.name: Education
element.documentation: All information regarding education and training that is necessary to be able to comply with the linked competencies.

element.name: Education Agreement
element.documentation: An agreement that regulates the rights and obligations in education-related matters between the educational institution and a participant. (source HORA)

element.name: Education participant
element.documentation: An individual who participates in educational activities. (source HORA)

element.name: Education program
element.documentation: Curriculum and study programming for regular (including medicine, nursing, paramedical) and further education (medical and nursing specializations). A collection of units of study that belong to a study program in a specific educational period. (source HORA)

element.name: Educational material
element.documentation: Material that is used in transferring or testing knowledge and competences. (source HORA)

element.name: Educational qualification
element.documentation: The extent to which the education offered meets predetermined criteria.

element.name: Enterprise architecture
element.documentation: A consistent set of principles and models that guide the design and realization of the (processes, organizational structure,) information provision, software development and technical infrastructure of an organization.

element.name: Evaluation report
element.documentation: Documentation of the conversation with the patient at the end of care, in which information is provided about aftercare, and in which the opinion and experiences of the patient about the care provided can be discussed.

element.name: Exam program
element.documentation: A participant-specific interpretation of an examination program, consisting of a set of educational units. (source HORA)

element.name: Exchange information
element.documentation: Information that is exchanged between healthcare providers / institutions. Specific instances are ”referral information” and “transfer information.”

element.name: External information, patient
element.documentation: External (medical) information, supplied by the patient.

element.name: Finding
element.documentation: Results of performed testing of processes/products/services within the institution. Not only the finding itself is recorded, the status and follow-up are also included. Examples include quality measurements and checks of medical equipment.

element.name: Hardware
element.documentation: All physical (touchable) parts of a computer and its peripherals. Monitors, routers, hubs, printers and scanners belong to the category of hardware, among others.

element.name: Health insurer
element.documentation: Healthcare insurance provider, contracting party for healthcare provider/care provider.

element.name: Healthcare Professional
element.documentation: Person who provides care professionally under a particular qualification and/or approval to do so from a competent authority.

element.name: Healthcare knowledge
element.documentation: Publications, professional literature, knowledge about healthcare.

element.name: Healthcare product
element.documentation: Administrative unit for a form of medical action or research that serves as the basis on which the declaration/invoicing of care takes place.

element.name: Healthcare provider
element.documentation: Organization that provides care under a specific qualification and/or approval for this from a competent authority.

element.name: History
element.documentation: Patient history, possibly (partly) obtained through referral information

element.name: Hospital policy
element.documentation: Guidelines for achieving hospital goals.

element.name: Housing plan
element.documentation: Description of current and desired accommodation requirements for temporary or permanent shelter

element.name: IT service
element.documentation: IT services such as: helpdesk, user support. IT services include presentation aggregation (portals), search engine, business intelligence (BI), web content management, knowledge creation and social media, email and calendar, telephone and video, speech recognition.

element.name: Information bulletin or news item
element.documentation: Internal or external messages/announcements that can be communicated by means of press releases, email, intranet, website, organizational magazines, staff newspaper, etc.

element.name: Informed Consent
element.documentation: Signed statement by a patient that they agree with what is specified in the statement, for example, with regard to nature, approach, and risk of scientific research, diagnosis or treatment that the patient is undergoing.

element.name: Innovation agenda
element.documentation: Strategic plan containing the direction and all associated activities aimed at innovation in an organization.

element.name: Internship/graduation activity
element.documentation: A learning activity in which a participant carries out an internship/graduation assignment. (HORA)

element.name: Internship/graduation assignment
element.documentation: A possible assignment for an internship or graduation.

element.name: Internship/graduation organization
element.documentation: An organization that offers internships/graduations to participants. (bon HORA)

element.name: Inventory
element.documentation: Household effects

element.name: Invoice
element.documentation: Overview of delivered products and services with associated prices, with the request to the addressee for payment.

element.name: Job Profile
element.documentation: Descriptions of tasks, responsibilities and required competences of professionals in a specific work situation and/or field

element.name: Labor contract
element.documentation: An agreement between employer and employee, whereby the employee undertakes to perform work for a number of hours per week in the employer's service. This can also be a volunteer or learning/work agreement.

element.name: Leaflets and brochures
element.documentation: Documents with medical information to support the primary process

element.name: Learning activity
element.documentation: A participant activity in which a participant acquires competences. (source HORA)

element.name: Learning group
element.documentation: A collection of participants carrying out common learning activities. (source HORA)

element.name: Learning materials
element.documentation: Educational materials that participants use to learn. (source HORA)

element.name: Legal advice
element.documentation: Legal advice on medical-ethical issues and the handling of claims and complaints

element.name: Location
element.documentation: Place or room where patient care (eg consultation, treatment and diagnostics) takes place.

element.name: Malfunction
element.documentation: Description of the nature of the malfunction and its handling

element.name: Market analysis
element.documentation: Research into the relationship between supply and demand in a particular market and the factors that influence it. Also uses SWOT analysis.

element.name: Material
element.documentation: A consumable within the healthcare institution that is used to support the process (e.g. durable medical equipment, medicine, beds, etc).

element.name: Means of transport
element.documentation: Means of transport with maintenance status, type, identification number, shed/parking details, lease contract

element.name: Measure
element.documentation: The activity of determining a quantitative/objective value.

element.name: Measurement
element.documentation: The result of determining a quantitative measure (for example, from a device, like a scale or monitor.)

element.name: Medical Index Scores
element.documentation: The result of determining a qualitative measure using a clinical assessment tool (for example, a questionnaire, index, scale, or other scoring tool).

element.name: Medical equipment
element.documentation: Physical machine units used in healthcare, for example, ultrasounds, lasers, audio and visual devices, PET cameras and X-ray machines.

element.name: Medication Administration
element.documentation: Description of the actual administration of a medication to a patient.

element.name: Medication agreement
element.documentation: Proposal by a healthcare provider in the role of prescriber for the use of medication by a patient.

element.name: Medication dispense
element.documentation: Description of the provision of a medicine.

element.name: Medication use
element.documentation: Recording of the intake or administration of prescribed or over-the-counter medication, as reported by the patient, an informal caregiver, or a health care provider.

element.name: Metadata
element.documentation: Information about the data. Definition of data (entities). All information needed for data management.

element.name: Minor
element.documentation: A collection of units of study that are offered as a whole. (source HORA)

element.name: Mission
element.documentation: The mission of an organization is a relatively static and concise description of the primary function(s), the mission or the raison d'être of the organization, which evolves little if at all over the years.

element.name: Nurse Diagnosis
element.documentation: Recording the name of the illness or condition that a person is believed to be suffering from, stated by the nurse.

element.name: Nurse Evaluation
element.documentation: Assessment of the nursing care provided, in which the opinion and experiences of the patient can also be discussed.

element.name: Nursing
element.documentation: Record nursing activities

element.name: Nursing Intervention
element.documentation: Intervention is a conditional activity that does not require an order. For example, the nursing plan may state: If the patient has a headache, give aspirin.

element.name: Nursing anamnesis (history)
element.documentation: Background and history of a patient, obtained through systematic questioning by a nurse

element.name: Nursing plan
element.documentation: Recording the plan with regard to the nursing care to be provided to the patient with the aim of alleviating or eliminating illness and health complaints.

element.name: Objective
element.documentation: Provide (additional) control to the processes within an organization, including financial planning, monitoring and adjusting the time and commitment of people.

element.name: Order
element.documentation: An order is synonymous with a request for something (an activity).

element.name: Organization structure
element.documentation: Elaboration of the way in which tasks are divided within an organization and the way in which coordination between subtasks is subsequently established.

element.name: Other HR
element.documentation: Other information objects for P&O include vacancy, applicant, volunteer and competence.

element.name: Overview studies
element.documentation: A complete overview of all ongoing investigations within the healthcare institution.

element.name: Participant education
element.documentation: An individual who participates in educational activities. (source HORA)

element.name: Patent
element.documentation: An exclusive property right for the invention of a technical product or process

element.name: Patient
element.documentation: Administrative information about the patient. This is a person who receives care (eg medical, paramedical or nursing) from a care provider.

element.name: Patient brochure
element.documentation: Information about a disease/treatment provided to the patient by a healthcare professional.

element.name: Patient health record
element.documentation: All data recorded about the patient.

element.name: Performance indicator
element.documentation: A quantifiable, measurable indication that shows whether an organization or organizational unit has succeeded in achieving a particular objective.

element.name: Person
element.documentation: Person who has a role in the care process, this can also be the patient.

element.name: Personnel file
element.documentation: Administrative data relating to staff

element.name: Physical examination result
element.documentation: Findings from the observations of examined bodily functions.

element.name: Plan
element.documentation: (Multi-year) plan for budget and organizational activities based on the objective.

element.name: Policies and Study Protocols
element.documentation: Applicable policy, legislation and regulations and protocols with which new research must comply and which are therefore preconditions for new research.

element.name: Preoperative Screening Report
element.documentation: Recording the findings of the preoperative screening.

element.name: Privacy Policy
element.documentation: Description of the way in which information about persons or groups is communicated to others and how personal freedom is safeguarded.

element.name: Procedure
element.documentation: Administrative code containing information about actions performed by a healthcare provider in the context of diagnosis or treatment.

element.name: Production appointments
element.documentation: Agreements between budgeted healthcare institutions and healthcare insurers about production, which are taken into account in the (cost) budget to be agreed for a particular year.

element.name: Production planning
element.documentation: Defining the goal and possibly, sub-goals, as well as procedures, to achieve intended production.

element.name: Products and services catalog
element.documentation: An overview of all products and services with associated descriptions that an organization offers.

element.name: Program
element.documentation: A set of related projects with a common goal.

element.name: Progress Report
element.documentation: The progress report is a periodic report from a contractor to the client. The report describes the status and progress of a specific appointment/assignment.

element.name: Project
element.documentation: A project is a (set of related) activity(ies) with a defined goal, limited in time and resources.

element.name: Project plan
element.documentation: Overviews of the steps that need to be taken to carry out a project.

element.name: Provision request
element.documentation: Medication prescription from a doctor to a pharmacist to provide the patient with a specific medication.

element.name: Publication list
element.documentation: Overview of all publications produced by the healthcare institution.

element.name: Quality documents
element.documentation: This includes regulations, protocols, manuals, guidelines and policies

element.name: Quality reporting
element.documentation: This includes all information related to quality accountability such as audits, among other things

element.name: Quotation
element.documentation: Indication of price and delivery conditions for an order or project from potential suppliers, requested by the purchaser.

element.name: Reference data
element.documentation: Reference data refers to data (often supplied by standardization organizations) which, apart from an incidental mutation, is static (unchangeable). Examples of reference data are: nations, place, postcodes, operations

element.name: Referral information
element.documentation: The information that a healthcare provider uses to refer a patient to another healthcare provider.

element.name: Referral order
element.documentation: Order to transfer a patient.

element.name: Referral request
element.documentation: Request to (sometimes temporarily) take over or take back the care of a patient.

element.name: Report
element.documentation: Record of a specific additional diagnostic test

element.name: Request/planning clinical movement
element.documentation: Request for planning and execution of a clinical movement (admission/discharge/transfer) care trajectory.

element.name: Research data
element.documentation: The data collected during the research.

element.name: Research material/specimen
element.documentation: The (biomedical) material collected during the scientific research (e.g. blood, tissue, etc.).

element.name: Research object
element.documentation: Basic data of the person or subject of research such as animal, patient, blood. Persons are recorded in a pseudonymized or anonymized manner.

element.name: Research proposal
element.documentation: Description of the design of the research, the research question, objective, etc.

element.name: Research protocol
element.documentation: Description of the protocol that will be followed during the study.

element.name: Research publication
element.documentation: Publications and information from scientific research.

element.name: Research report
element.documentation: Record of the complete additional findings

element.name: Research report, dissertation, publication
element.documentation: The results from registrations and analysis of the project are processed into a final report (publication, dissertation or presentation).

element.name: Research request
element.documentation: Request to conduct research

element.name: Research support
element.documentation: Information for the substantive and administrative support of research.

element.name: Resource
element.documentation: People and other non-material assets that are used within a healthcare institution to support the healthcare process

element.name: Result
element.documentation: Recording the result of an activity.

element.name: Result collegiate consultation
element.documentation: Information about the outcome of a request for peer consultation.

element.name: Results of own research
element.documentation: Findings of the research conducted by the healthcare provider himself.

element.name: Risk analysis
element.documentation: Assessment of the probability and possible consequences of the occurrence of various types of hazards in and around the facility, including hazards that may be caused by the interaction between individual activities and existing installations.

element.name: Roadmap
element.documentation: A roadmap is a strategic plan for the further development of a specific area (product, technology, etc.) and is directly linked to the strategic objectives of the organization. The roadmap provides a commonly agreed description of the direction and associated objectives needed to achieve the business objectives in the coming years.

element.name: Schedule
element.documentation: An overview with dates and times in which the availability (occupied and open slots) of one resource is recorded.

element.name: Scheduling Services
element.documentation: Overview of reserved, reservable and returned services

element.name: Score
element.documentation: The activity of determining a qualitative/perceived value.

element.name: Self-management information
element.documentation: Information yet to be validated by the treating physician obtained from the patient as a result of their own care process (self measurement, diary reports, images, etc.). This can be obtained for example, from completed questionnaires or a personal health file.

element.name: Services
element.documentation: Offered service or product such as parking, catering, shops, (meeting) space, telecom facilities, mobility equipment, waste, sterilization, repro, post, etc.

element.name: Software
element.documentation: The operating and application programs, procedures, and associated documentation related to the operation of a computer system.

element.name: Specimen
element.documentation: Human body, or material derived from the human body on which research can be carried out for the purpose of diagnosis, treatment or scientific research.

element.name: Statutory VKAM registrations
element.documentation: Recording of data based on statutory obligations for safety, quality, labor, and enviornment (VKAM in Dutch) such as hazardous substances registration, radiation hygiene, and environmental registration.

element.name: Strategy
element.documentation: The multi-year approach elaborated by the management in order to realize the vision and mission. Planned and targeted deployment of people and resources to realize policy decisions in order to realize the vision and mission of the organization and the goals derived from it.

element.name: Supplier
element.documentation: The natural or legal person who supplies goods

element.name: Surgery
element.documentation: Description of the intended or performed surgical intervention.

element.name: Surgery report
element.documentation: Recording of the course of an surgery performed, including materials used.

element.name: Teaching materials
element.documentation: Teaching materials and educational information.

element.name: Technical installation
element.documentation: Technical facilities incl. specifications (descriptions, instruction, manuals, etc.) such as heating, air conditioning, water pipes, etc.

element.name: Test activity
element.documentation: A participant activity that examines the knowledge, insight and skills of a participant and that should lead to a test result. (source HORA)

element.name: Test material
element.documentation: Educational materials used for testing. Typically consists of a set of questions and rules about how answers to the questions are judged. (source HORA)

element.name: Test result
element.documentation: The result of performing a test activity (for example: grade, attendance, completion of internship). (source HORA)

element.name: Therapeutic Diagnosis
element.documentation: Recording the name of the disease or condition from which a person is believed to be suffering.

element.name: Therapeutic History
element.documentation: Background and history of a patient, obtained through systematic questioning by a paramedical care provider.

element.name: Therapy
element.documentation: Request for treatment, carried out by a specific paramedical discipline, eg physiotherapy, speech therapy.

element.name: Therapy plan
element.documentation: Establishing the plan with regard to the paramedical care to be provided to the patient, with the aim of alleviating or removing health complaints or defects.

element.name: Therapy report
element.documentation: Recording of the therapy performed by the paramedical care provider.

element.name: Timetable
element.documentation: The collection of educational activities scheduled in time, linked to the necessary resources and employees. (source HORA)

element.name: Training education
element.documentation: A coherent whole of education units, aimed at achieving competences or objectives in the field of knowledge, insight, attitudes and skills that the person completing the study program must possess. (source HORA)

element.name: Transfer information
element.documentation: Selection of data from the file intended for the transfer of the patient.

element.name: Transfer policy
element.documentation: Patient transfer policy, including reason, treatment goal and destination.

element.name: Treatment
element.documentation: Treatment of the patient, other than medical, surgical, paramedical, nursing or caring.

element.name: Treatment options
element.documentation: The treatment options that are identified during the consultation and the diagnostic process.

element.name: Treatment plan
element.documentation: Recording the plan with regard to the care to be provided to the patient with the aim of alleviating or removing health complaints or ailments.

element.name: Treatment report
element.documentation: Documentation of the treatment of the patient, other than medical, surgical, paramedical, nursing or caring.

element.name: Unit result
element.documentation: The composite result of a unit of study based on underlying test results. (source HORA)

element.name: VKAM advice
element.documentation: Advising in safety, quality, labor, and enviornment (VKAM in Dutch) field such as purchase and implementation of new equipment, prevention, etc.

element.name: VKAM plan
element.documentation: Established policy or plans in the areas of safety, quality, labor, and enviornment (??VKAM in Dutch)

element.name: Vision
element.documentation: An inspiring vision of the future for the organization that distances itself from daily practice.

element.name: Work product
element.documentation: An artifact created as part of an activity. Examples are a thesis, report, paper, dissertation or photos of physical products that have been made.

element.name: ledger
element.documentation: The collection of all ledger accounts with the changes that occur during a certain period.

element.name: AbilityToDessOneself
element.documentation: ! Attention: this information model is undergoing major revision. A new version will be available after summer. Being able to get dressed independently is part of self-care. Limitations in this ability indicate a reduced ability to cope for oneself. element.name: AbilityToPerformHaircareActivities

(Bron: Instructiekaart Mondverzorging, 2011) {</nl-NL><en-US>! Attention: this information model is undergoing major revision. A new version will be available after summer. element.name: AdvanceDirecrtive
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Een wilsverklaring is een mondelinge of schriftelijke omschrijving van de wens van de patiënt ten aanzien van toekomstig medisch handelen of het levenseinde. Een wilsverklaring is vooral voor situaties waarin de patiënt niet meer over deze beslissingen kan praten met de zorgverlener. {</nl-NL><en-US>A living will is a verbal or written description of the patient's wishes with regard to future medical action or end of their life. A living will is mainly used for situations in which the patient is no longer able to speak about these decisions with their healthcare provider.</en-US></language>

element.name: AlcoholUse
element.documentation: In the context of this information model, alcohol is the collective term for alcoholic beverages consumed as a leisure product. This information model describes the information asked of the patient about their alcohol use.

element.name: Alert
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Een alert beschrijft een klinisch of administratief feit dat onder de aandacht van de gebruikers van de klinische systemen wordt gebracht , om er bij het vormen van diagnostisch en therapeutisch beleid of bij de omgang met de patiënt rekening mee te houden, meestal wegens een veiligheidsrisico. Aandoeningen, die de overgevoeligheid van het lichaam voor een stof beschrijven, zich uitend in een specifieke fysiologische reactie na blootstelling, worden allergieën genoemd. Deze worden in een aparte bouwsteen beschreven. Waarschuwingen voor niet allergische aandoeningen kunnen betreffen: -een aandoening (conditie of diagnose die beschouwd kan worden als contra-indicatie voor het gebruik van groepen van geneesmiddelen of het ondergaan van een bepaalde therapie), zoals zwangerschap of een verlengd QT-syndroom -Verminderde functie van een orgaansysteem (hartfalen, verminder lever- of nierfunctie, verminderde afweer) -Kans op verspreiding van bepaalde micro-organismen (multiresistente bacterie, tuberkelbacterie, HIV, HBV, Ebola virus) -Andere risico's {</nl-NL><en-US>An alert describes a clinical or administrative fact brought to the attention of the users of the clinical systems to be taken into account when shaping diagnostic and therapeutic policy or in dealing with the patient, usually because of a safety risk. Disorders that describe the body's sensitivity to a substance which results in a specific physiological reaction after being exposed to that substance are referred to as allergies. These are described in a separate information model. Warnings for non-allergic disorders can concern: - A disorder (condition or diagnosis which can be considered as a contraindication for the use of groups of medication or undergoing a certain type of therapy), such as pregnancy or long QT syndrome - Impaired functioning of an organ system (heart failure, impaired liver or kidney function, weakened immune system) - Risk of spreading certain microorganisms (multi-resistant bacteria, tubercle bacilli, HIV, HBV, Ebola virus) - Other risks</en-US></language>

element.name: AllergyIntolerance
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>Een allergie of intolerantie beschrijft de geneigdheid tot overgevoeligheid van een patiënt voor een stof, zodat na blootstelling een ongewenste fysiologische reactie verwacht wordt, terwijl bij de meeste mensen bij die hoeveelheid geen reactie zou optreden. De waargenomen fysiologische veranderingen zijn meestal het resultaat van een immunologische reactie. De stoffen kunnen als volgt worden ingedeeld: -Geneesmiddel -Geneesmiddelgroep -Ingrediënt/toevoeging -Voeding -Omgevingsfactor -Dier -Planten -Chemicaliën -Inhalatieallergenen {</nl-NL><en-US>An allergy or intolerance describes a patient's tendency towards hypersensitivity to a certain substance, so that an unwanted physiological reaction is expected after exposure to the substance, while most people would not exhibit such a reaction to that amount. The observed physiological changes are usually the result of an immunological reaction. The substances can be categorized as follows: - Medicine - Medicine category - Ingredient/addition - Nutrition - Environmental factor - Animal - Plants - Chemicals - Inhaled allergenic</en-US></language>

element.name: BarthelADLIndex
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>De Barthel-index is een gevalideerd meetinstrument voor het vastleggen en volgen van activiteiten van het dagelijks leven (ADL) van patiënten en indirect de mate van afhankelijk zijn van hulp. De lijst bestaat uit 10 onderdelen: darm, blaas, uiterlijke verzorging, toiletgebruik, eten, transfers (bed-stoel en omgekeerd), mobiliteit, aan- en uitkleden, trappen lopen en baden/douchen waaraan een score wordt toegekend. De totaalscore is de som van de scores van de 10 onderdelen. {</nl-NL><en-US>The Barthel ADL index is a validated scale used to measure and track patients' activities of daily living (ADL) and indirectly, the extent to which they are dependent on help. The list comprises 10 variables: bowels, bladder, grooming, toilet use, feeding, transfers (from chair to bed and vice versa), mobility, dressing, climbing stairs and bathing, which are all given a score. The total score is the sum of the scores of the 10 variables.</en-US></language>

element.name: BladderFunction
element.documentation: ! Attention: this information model is undergoing major revision. A new version will be available after summer. The primary function of the bladder is temporary storage of urine. A second important function of the bladder is secretion of the stored urine at the moment there is cause to do so. These functions can be disrupted due to various causes.

element.name: BodyHeight
element.documentation: <languages xml:space="preserve"><nl-NL>De lichaamslengte van een persoon. {</nl-NL><en-US>A person's body height.</en-US></language>

element.name: BodyTemperature

element.name: BodyWeight

element.name: BowerlFunction
